meta.type_name: Cooking steps where temporal sequence determines outcome

patterns.linguistic_principle: Iconicity - cooking steps mirror actual sequence of physical actions
patterns.example: Preheat oven to 350°F → Place dough on baking sheet → Bake until golden brown, about 15 minutes
patterns.why_asymmetric: Steps must occur in physical time order; reversing breaks procedural logic and causes failure
patterns.real_world_application: Recipes, assembly instructions, procedural documentation

patterns.structure: complementary_technique ↔ alternative_technique (different methods achieving same goal)
patterns.example: Whisk egg whites until stiff peaks form ↔ Use stand mixer on high for 3-4 minutes
patterns.why_symmetric: Both provide actionable methods; each elaborates on the other's approach

patterns.description: Cooking facts that share ingredients/tools but provide no procedural value
patterns.why_negative: Domain-relevant facts that don't advance the cooking procedure

meta.type_name: Physical construction where component order determines structural integrity

patterns.linguistic_principle: Iconicity - assembly sequence mirrors physical construction reality
patterns.example: Attach metal frame to base plate → Slide wooden panel into frame slots → Tighten corner screws clockwise until snug
patterns.why_asymmetric: Later steps physically depend on earlier completion; reverse order is impossible
patterns.real_world_application: Furniture assembly, device setup, construction manuals

patterns.structure: tool_option_A ↔ tool_option_B (interchangeable tools for same step)
patterns.example: Use Phillips screwdriver for cross-head screws ↔ Power drill with PH2 bit works faster
patterns.why_symmetric: Both explain tool selection; each helps understand the other's trade-offs

patterns.description: Component specifications that don't guide assembly sequence
patterns.why_negative: Material facts relevant to domain but useless for step execution

meta.type_name: Diagnostic and fix sequences where causal understanding drives action

patterns.linguistic_principle: Cause must precede effect - diagnosis enables targeted solution
patterns.example: Faucet drips constantly → Worn rubber washer in valve seat → Replace washer with 1/2-inch neoprene washer
patterns.why_asymmetric: Solution makes sense only after cause; symptom alone doesn't enable action
patterns.real_world_application: Home repair, automotive troubleshooting, appliance fixes

patterns.structure: diagnostic_method_A ↔ diagnostic_method_B (alternative ways to identify cause)
patterns.example: Check for water pooling under sink ↔ Run water and observe valve stem for leaks
patterns.why_symmetric: Both diagnostic approaches inform each other; provide complementary evidence

patterns.description: Related maintenance facts that don't solve the current problem
patterns.why_negative: General maintenance advice that doesn't address specific failure

meta.type_name: Critical procedures where temporal order prevents harm escalation

patterns.linguistic_principle: Iconicity - response steps mirror time-critical physical reality
patterns.example: Turn off gas valve at meter → Open windows for ventilation → Call gas company from outside the building
patterns.why_asymmetric: Safety requires specific order; reversing creates danger or wastes critical time
patterns.real_world_application: First aid, emergency procedures, safety protocols

patterns.structure: warning_sign_A ↔ warning_sign_B (correlated indicators of same emergency)
patterns.example: Strong sulfur odor indicates gas leak ↔ Hissing sound near gas lines indicates leak
patterns.why_symmetric: Both signs help recognize emergency; each validates the other

patterns.description: Safety facts that don't guide immediate emergency response
examples: Natural gas is odorless; mercaptan is added for detection
patterns.why_negative: Educational context that doesn't help in time-critical situations

meta.type_name: Code errors where understanding cause enables targeted fixes

patterns.linguistic_principle: Cause-effect - root cause must be understood before solution makes sense
patterns.example: API returns 500 errors intermittently → Database connection pool exhausted under load → Increase pool size from 10 to 50 and add connection timeout
patterns.why_asymmetric: Fix only makes sense after diagnosis; error alone doesn't reveal what to change
patterns.real_world_application: Software debugging, log analysis, performance optimization

patterns.example: Add logging statements to trace execution flow ↔ Use debugger breakpoints to inspect state
patterns.why_symmetric: Both techniques aid diagnosis; each illuminates strengths of the other

patterns.description: Code architecture facts that don't solve the specific error
patterns.why_negative: Tech stack information relevant to domain but useless for this specific bug

meta.type_name: Connectivity issues where layer-by-layer diagnosis reveals cause

patterns.linguistic_principle: Causal chain - each diagnostic step reveals deeper cause
patterns.example: Cannot reach website at example.com → DNS lookup fails; /etc/resolv.conf points to wrong nameserver → Update nameserver to 8.8.8.8 in resolv.conf
patterns.why_asymmetric: Resolution requires knowing what's broken; symptom doesn't indicate fix location
patterns.real_world_application: Network administration, IT support, DevOps troubleshooting

patterns.structure: diagnostic_tool_A ↔ diagnostic_tool_B (tools revealing same layer's status)
patterns.example: Use ping to test IP connectivity ↔ Use traceroute to identify routing path
patterns.why_symmetric: Both diagnose network layer; results complement each other's findings

patterns.description: Network architecture facts that don't diagnose current problem
patterns.why_negative: Infrastructure details that don't reveal this specific failure point

meta.type_name: Physical component failures requiring cause identification before replacement

patterns.linguistic_principle: Diagnostic causation - symptoms lead to component identification
patterns.example: Laptop won't power on → Power supply unit outputs 0V; internal fuse blown → Replace PSU with 65W 19V adapter matching original specs
patterns.why_asymmetric: Knowing what failed enables targeted replacement; symptom alone could be multiple causes
patterns.real_world_application: Electronics repair, computer maintenance, appliance servicing

patterns.structure: test_method_A ↔ test_method_B (alternative ways to confirm component failure)
patterns.example: Use multimeter to test PSU voltage output ↔ Swap PSU with known-good unit to verify
patterns.why_symmetric: Both confirm diagnosis; each method validates the other's conclusion

patterns.description: Hardware specifications that don't identify failed component
examples: Laptop has Intel Core i5 processor
patterns.why_negative: Specs relevant to device but don't diagnose which part failed

meta.type_name: Explaining complex ideas by building from familiar foundations

patterns.linguistic_principle: Given→New - anchor familiar concept before introducing novel information
patterns.example: You know arrays store data in sequential memory → Hash tables store data using computed key positions → They use hash function modulo table size to map keys to indices
patterns.why_asymmetric: New concept needs familiar foundation; starting with technical detail loses audience
patterns.real_world_application: Technical documentation, educational content, onboarding materials

patterns.structure: concept_aspect_A ↔ concept_aspect_B (complementary facets of same concept)
patterns.example: Hash tables offer O(1) average lookup time ↔ Hash tables trade memory for speed with load factor management
patterns.why_symmetric: Both illuminate trade-offs; each property helps understand the other

patterns.description: Related technical facts that don't build understanding from current foundation
examples: Python dict uses hash tables internally
patterns.why_negative: Historical or implementation trivia that doesn't teach the concept

meta.type_name: Teaching scientific concepts from observable phenomena to theory

patterns.linguistic_principle: Given→New - start with observable experience, build to principle
patterns.example: Ice floats on water → Water molecules form crystalline structure when frozen, increasing volume → This hydrogen bonding anomaly makes water less dense as solid than liquid
patterns.why_asymmetric: Abstract principle makes sense after observable anchor; reversing loses intuition
patterns.real_world_application: Science education, popular science writing, explanatory journalism

patterns.structure: evidence_type_A ↔ evidence_type_B (different evidence supporting same principle)
patterns.example: Ice expansion cracks rocks in freeze-thaw cycles ↔ Frozen water pipes burst from pressure buildup
patterns.why_symmetric: Both demonstrate same principle; each example reinforces the other

patterns.description: Related science facts that don't explain the principle being taught
examples: Ice has been found on Mars
patterns.why_negative: Topically related but doesn't build epistemic understanding

meta.type_name: Teaching business frameworks by connecting to familiar contexts

patterns.linguistic_principle: Given→New - relate abstract business concept to concrete experience
patterns.example: You've chosen restaurants based on reviews and convenience → This is evaluating switching costs and network effects → Businesses use these same factors to analyze competitive moats
patterns.why_asymmetric: Framework makes sense after concrete grounding; abstract term first is opaque
patterns.real_world_application: Business education, management training, strategy consulting

patterns.example: High switching costs retain customers longer ↔ Network effects increase value for all users
patterns.why_symmetric: Both create competitive advantage; each mechanism amplifies the other

patterns.description: Business jargon or facts that don't teach the framework
patterns.why_negative: Business trivia that doesn't build conceptual understanding

meta.type_name: Teaching history by connecting events to familiar narratives

patterns.linguistic_principle: Given→New - anchor to known history before introducing new events
patterns.example: You know the Cold War involved US-Soviet tensions → The Berlin Airlift was a 1948 crisis when Soviets blocked West Berlin → This event crystallized the policy of containment that defined the next 40 years
patterns.why_asymmetric: New event makes sense within known context; isolated fact lacks meaning
patterns.real_world_application: History education, documentary narratives, museum exhibits

patterns.structure: perspective_A ↔ perspective_B (different viewpoints on same event)
patterns.example: Western powers saw airlift as defending freedom ↔ Soviet Union viewed it as provocative interference in their sphere
patterns.why_symmetric: Both perspectives illuminate motivations; each clarifies the other's reasoning

patterns.description: Historical facts that don't connect to the narrative being built
patterns.why_negative: Factual details that don't build epistemic understanding of significance

meta.type_name: Question-answer pairs where question creates expectation for response

patterns.linguistic_principle: Adjacency pairs - question creates obligation for answer
patterns.example: How do I prevent SQL injection in Node.js? → Use parameterized queries with prepared statements → Example: db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?', [userId])
patterns.why_asymmetric: Answer addresses question; question doesn't help someone implementing answer
patterns.real_world_application: Stack Overflow, support forums, documentation FAQs

patterns.example: Are you using PostgreSQL or MySQL? ↔ I'm using PostgreSQL 13 with pg library
patterns.why_symmetric: Both refine context; each response enables more specific help

patterns.description: Related technical information that doesn't answer the question
examples: SQL injection is in OWASP Top 10
patterns.why_negative: Background information that doesn't fulfill answer obligation

meta.type_name: Service requests and responses following interactional norms

patterns.linguistic_principle: Request-response pairs - request creates expectation for fulfillment
patterns.example: I need to cancel my subscription → I can help with that. Can you confirm your account email? → Once confirmed, I'll process cancellation effective immediately
patterns.why_asymmetric: Response addresses request; request doesn't help execute the action
patterns.real_world_application: Customer service chats, help desk tickets, support calls

patterns.example: What's your order number? ↔ It's #12345, placed on January 15th
patterns.why_symmetric: Both pieces needed for resolution; each enables the other's usefulness

patterns.description: Company policies that don't address the specific request
patterns.why_negative: Generic statements that don't fulfill interactional obligation

meta.type_name: Seeking and providing guidance following conversational norms

patterns.linguistic_principle: Advice-seeking creates expectation for recommendation
patterns.example: I have $10k to invest and I'm 25 years old → Consider low-cost index funds for long-term growth → At your age, you can ride out market volatility for decades of compound growth
patterns.why_asymmetric: Advice responds to situation; situation doesn't help implement advice
patterns.real_world_application: Reddit advice forums, mentorship conversations, consulting

patterns.example: I'm risk-averse and need emergency access ↔ I have stable income and no debt
patterns.why_symmetric: Both constraints shape advice; each detail refines the other's relevance

patterns.description: General wisdom that doesn't address specific situation
examples: Past performance doesn't guarantee future returns
patterns.why_negative: Generic disclaimers that don't fulfill advice obligation

meta.type_name: Proposal-response pairs for arranging meetings and events

patterns.linguistic_principle: Proposal creates expectation for acceptance/counter-proposal
patterns.example: Can we meet Tuesday at 2pm to discuss the project? → Tuesday works, but I'm free after 3pm → Perfect, I'll send a 3pm calendar invite for Conference Room B
patterns.why_asymmetric: Response addresses proposal; proposal doesn't contain logistics details
patterns.real_world_application: Email coordination, calendar scheduling, meeting planning

patterns.example: I'm available Monday through Wednesday ↔ I can do Tuesday or Wednesday afternoons
patterns.why_symmetric: Both constraints needed for resolution; each narrows viable options

patterns.description: Meeting context that doesn't address scheduling logistics
examples: We should invite the design team
patterns.why_negative: Topically related but doesn't fulfill proposal-response obligation

meta.type_name: Specific errors entailing general categories with system implications

patterns.linguistic_principle: Entailment - specific instance implies general category, not vice versa
patterns.example: ECONNREFUSED on port 5432 → Database connection failure → All data-dependent endpoints will return 503 errors
patterns.why_asymmetric: Specific error entails general failure; general category doesn't specify which error
patterns.real_world_application: Error handling systems, logging infrastructure, monitoring dashboards

patterns.structure: error_indicator_A ↔ error_indicator_B (correlated symptoms of same root issue)
patterns.example: Connection timeout after 30 seconds ↔ No TCP handshake completion logged
patterns.why_symmetric: Both indicate same underlying issue; each validates the other's diagnosis

patterns.description: Error information that doesn't reveal category or impact
patterns.why_negative: Contextual details that don't enable semantic categorization

meta.type_name: Specific products belonging to general categories with attribute inheritance

patterns.linguistic_principle: Hyponymy - specific item inherits properties of general category
patterns.example: MacBook Air M2 → Laptop computer → Requires charging, portable computing device
patterns.why_asymmetric: Specific product IS-A laptop; laptop category doesn't specify which product
patterns.real_world_application: E-commerce categorization, inventory systems, search filtering

patterns.example: Has 13-inch Retina display ↔ Weighs 2.7 pounds for portability
patterns.why_symmetric: Both features describe the product; each attribute complements the other

patterns.description: Product facts that don't establish categorical relationships
patterns.why_negative: Product details that don't reveal taxonomic position or inherited attributes

meta.type_name: Specific conditions as instances of general diagnostic categories

patterns.linguistic_principle: Taxonomic entailment - specific diagnosis implies general condition class
patterns.example: Type 2 diabetes mellitus → Metabolic disorder → Requires lifestyle modification and possible medication management
patterns.why_asymmetric: Specific diagnosis entails metabolic disorder; category doesn't specify diabetes
patterns.real_world_application: Medical coding, clinical decision support, health records

patterns.example: Elevated fasting blood glucose levels ↔ Increased thirst and urination
patterns.why_symmetric: Both symptoms indicate condition; each finding supports the other

patterns.description: Medical facts that don't establish diagnostic hierarchy
patterns.why_negative: Epidemiological or historical info that doesn't reveal categorical relationship

meta.type_name: Specific rulings as instances of general legal principles

patterns.linguistic_principle: Legal entailment - specific case exemplifies general principle
patterns.example: Miranda v. Arizona (1966) → Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination → Police must inform suspects of rights before custodial interrogation
patterns.why_asymmetric: Specific case establishes principle; principle doesn't uniquely identify case
patterns.real_world_application: Legal research, case law databases, judicial reasoning

patterns.example: Right to remain silent ↔ Right to attorney before questioning
patterns.why_symmetric: Both rights work together; each clarifies scope of the other

patterns.description: Legal facts that don't establish principle-case relationship
patterns.why_negative: Procedural details that don't reveal doctrinal categorization

meta.type_name: Narrative events where temporal sequence creates coherent story

patterns.linguistic_principle: Narrative iconicity - story order reflects chronological event sequence
patterns.example: She submitted her resume on Monday → The hiring manager called her on Wednesday → She started the new job two weeks later
patterns.why_asymmetric: Events follow causal time order; reversing breaks narrative coherence
patterns.real_world_application: News articles, case studies, historical accounts, storytelling

patterns.example: She prepared for the interview by researching the company ↔ She practiced answering common interview questions
patterns.why_symmetric: Both preparations happened concurrently; each activity complements the other

patterns.description: Background details that don't advance narrative timeline
examples: She had been job hunting for three months
patterns.why_negative: Contextual information that doesn't create temporal progression
